## Cycle Plan

```yaml
- id: C1
  goal: <human-readable cycle goal — e.g. "implement the user storage layer">
  files_affected:
    - src/storage/users.ts
    - src/storage/types.ts
  acceptance: [AC-001]
  goal_condition: |
    cycles/C1/result.json exists with status: pass AND
    cycles/C1/review.md has 0 critical clusters,
    or stop after 30 turns

- id: C2
  goal: <…>
  files_affected: [<…>]
  acceptance: [AC-002]
  goal_condition: |
    cycles/C2/result.json exists with status: pass AND
    cycles/C2/review.md has 0 critical clusters,
    or stop after 30 turns

- id: C3
  goal: <final cycle — includes e2e wiring>
  files_affected: [<…>]
  acceptance: [AC-003]
  e2e_covers: [E-001, E-002]
  goal_condition: |
    cycles/C3/result.json exists with status: pass AND
    cycles/C3/review.md has 0 critical clusters AND
    e2e scenarios E-001, E-002 are exercised by tests in this cycle,
    or stop after 30 turns
```

> Cycles run **sequentially**. The outer goal session reads this block,
> picks the next pending cycle, and spawns one `claude -p` child per
> cycle.

## /goal Conditions

### Outer goal (top-level invocation)

```text
claude -p "/goal every cycle id in .forge/spec.md ## Cycle Plan
       has produced a cycles/<id>/result.json file containing
       status: pass — as observed in this session's transcript
       via narration of each child session's exit — or stop
       after K outer turns"
```

`K_outer ≈ len(cycles) + 5`.

### Per-cycle child goal

```text
claude -p "/goal cycles/<id>/result.json exists with
       status: pass AND cycles/<id>/review.md has 0 critical
       clusters as surfaced in this transcript,
       or stop after K_child turns"
```

`K_child = 30` typical; raise to 50 for known-hard cycles.

### Codex G2.a / G2.b wrappers (planner phase, internal)

```text
"/goal Codex via codex-bridge has responded AGREE on the latest revision
       of spec.md, or stop after 3 turns"
```

Codex stays as the judge — `/goal` just times out the loop after 3
attempts. Replaces the hand-rolled retry-counter from v0.1.0.

## Reviewer Config

```yaml
model: opus            # or sonnet
dimensions:
  - correctness        # ★ default
  - simplicity         # ★ default
  - security           # ★ default
  # additional Tier 1: design, error-handling, tests-vs-impl
  # Tier 2: performance, naming-readability, dependency-hygiene,
  #         type-safety, concurrency, observability
  # Tier 3 (declare per-project as needed):
  #         sui-move-idioms, frontend-a11y, api-contract-stability
```

- The **length of `dimensions`** = number of reviewers dispatched per
  cycle.
- Want 2 security reviewers? List `security` twice.
- `model` is passed through to each reviewer's `Agent` dispatch.

## Reviewer Prompt

The cycle child instantiates this template for each entry in
`dimensions`, substituting `{dimension}` and the per-cycle diff.

```text
You are a code reviewer for a code-forge cycle.

Your assigned dimension: {dimension}

Read the cycle plan entry (.forge/spec.md ## Cycle Plan, matching the
cycle id passed in your prompt) for files_affected + acceptance.
Read tests.json. Read the impl diff. Review specifically through the
{dimension} lens — see agents/reviewer.md for the dimension-to-lens map.

For each finding, emit JSON per agents/reviewer.md's output schema.

Write your findings to cycles/<id>/reviewers/subagent-<K>.json.
```

> The consolidator subagent reads all `subagent-*.json`, clusters by
> file+line proximity (inline, no `_consolidated.json` intermediate),
> re-verifies critical/high findings against source, and writes the
> final `cycles/<id>/review.md` with a machine-readable Cluster summary
> block the cycle child parses.

